The moment generating function of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is most easily computed by the law of iterated expectation as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{Y}(t)=E\left(e^{tY}\right)=E\left[E\left(e^{tY}|\Lambda=\lambda\right)\right]=E\left[e^{\lambda(e^{t}-1)}\right]=\psi_{\Lambda}(e^{t}-1)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{\Lambda}(t)=\frac{1}{1-at}
\]

\end_inset

 is the moment generating function for the 
\begin_inset Formula $Exp(a)$
\end_inset

 distribution, which exists if 
\begin_inset Formula $t<1/a$
\end_inset

.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{Y}(t)=\psi_{\Lambda}(e^{t}-1)=\frac{1}{1-a(e^{t}-1)},
\]

\end_inset

which exists if 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{t}-1<1/a$
\end_inset

, that is if 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{t}<1+\frac{1}{a}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $t<\ln(1+\frac{1}{a})$
\end_inset

.
