The distribution function of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{Z_{n}}(z)=P(Z_{n}\leq z)=1-P(Z_{n}>z)=1-P(X_{1}>z,X_{2}>z,...,X_{n}>z)
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the minimum and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{n}>z$
\end_inset

 is therefore the same as all 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},...,X_{n}$
\end_inset

 being larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Now, because of independence and that all 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{k}$
\end_inset

 have same distribution, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{Z_{n}}(z)=1-\left(1-F_{X}(z)\right)^{n}=1-\left(1-\left[1-\exp(-\frac{z}{a})\right]\right)^{n}=1-\exp\left(-\frac{nz}{a}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and the density is therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{Z}(z)=\frac{1}{(a/n)}\exp\exp\left(-\frac{z}{a/n}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\sim Exp(\frac{a}{n})$
\end_inset

.
